    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Blanket of Spray in the Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Ellen B Tabor letter disputes July 25 article on closing of Central Park following discovery of mosquities carrying West Nile virus</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Urban Mosquitoes'' (editorial, July 25):</p>
        <p>You say Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani ''had little choice'' but to spray Central Park once mosquitoes infected with the West Nile virus had been detected there. But spraying may have unpredictable adverse effects on our environment. The consequences are unknown.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Urban Mosquitoes'' (editorial, July 25):</p>
        <p>You say Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani ''had little choice'' but to spray Central Park once mosquitoes infected with the West Nile virus had been detected there. But spraying may have unpredictable adverse effects on our environment. The consequences are unknown.</p>
        <p>Our climate is changing, and while today it is mosquitoes and the West Nile virus, what new pathogen will emerge tomorrow? We cannot destroy all lesser life forms to prevent human illness; soon, we will inhabit a world that cannot provide us food and clean water because of our efforts at environmental control.</p>
        <p>Rather than spray toxins over the populace, better for us to wear protective clothing, use nontoxic insect repellents, fix broken screens and modify our schedules so that we are not out when the mosquitoes are.</p>
        <p>ELLEN B. TABOR, M.D.  New York, July 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
